fields.text: Which is not an Operating System?
fields.explanation: Microsoft Office XP is a suite of desktop applications, including text editor, spreadsheet editor, etc, NOT an operating system.

fields.text: How many bytes is one kilobyte?
fields.explanation: Although kilobyte is formally equal to 1000 bytes, a second definition and usage of 1024 bytes has historically been in practice in the field of computer science and IT.

fields.text: What type of data structure is a queue?
fields.explanation: First In First Out. Picture a queue of people -- the first person (data item) in the queue is the first to leave the queue at the front. Additional people (data items) join at the back of the queue.

fields.text: What might you use to automate tasks in Microsoft Office?
fields.explanation: Macro's can automate tasks in Microsoft Office, but can also be used maliciously to cause harm.

fields.text: Which of the following would be capable of printing, scanning and copying?
fields.explanation: An MFD or MultiFunction Device (sometimes known as MFP or MultiFunction Printer) allows printing, scanning and copying.

fields.text: Which of the following Microsoft products is primarily used for databases?
fields.explanation: Microsoft Access is used to create databases.

fields.text: How might a computer actively block outside connections from harmful sources?
fields.explanation: A firewall can block incoming and outgoing connections. Optionaly, certain connections can be allowed.

fields.text: Who is the owner of Microsoft?
fields.explanation: Bill Gates is the founder and owner of the Microsoft Corporation.

fields.text: Which is the most common use for 'task manager' in Windows?
fields.explanation: Task manager has many uses but is most commonly used for stopping unresponsive software. It can also be used to start and end tasks, and see what resources are being used by what tasks, and can do much more.

fields.text: What does formatting a hard drive do?
fields.explanation: Formatting a hard drive wipes information from it. It will also mark any bad sectors of the disk.

fields.text: Where might you find the option to change the screen resolution on a Windows computer?
fields.explanation: The display settings on a Windows computer will have the option to change the resolution. Some graphics adaptors will have their own software that will also do this (eg an NVIDIA graphics card).
There are many other layouts of keys on keyboards designed for comfort and speed, but the qwerty layout is by far the most common.

fields.text: What type of connection would NOT be used to connect a mouse/keyboard to a personal computer?
fields.explanation: A parallel port is used to connnect scanners and printers and other such devices to computers, although parallel is an old standard and has been replaced for the most part by USB.

fields.text: Which of the following devices has NOT TYPICALLY got a microprocessor in it?
fields.explanation: A typical analogue clock is a mechanical device that does not use microprocessor technology. Most electrical appliances DO contain a microprocessor - microwaves, TV, DVD player, modern TV's etc.

fields.text: Which of the following is LEAST likely to cause a computer to overheat?
fields.explanation: A full hard drive is unlikely to produce much excess heat. All other answers are very plausible and common causes for overheating.

fields.text: Which of these is a Microsoft operating system?
fields.explanation: Windows Vista was Microsoft's next major release after Windows XP.
Wifi - Wireless Fidelity - a technology used for wireless networking of computers and other network devices.

fields.text: What extension has a typical Microsoft Office Word 2003 file?
fields.explanation: Office 2003 Word files use the .doc extension.

fields.text: A Microsoft Exchange server is used for what?
fields.explanation: Exchange servers are used for managing e-mail. They also manage calendars and contacts.

fields.text: What is the preferred method to quickly and directly upload a file to a web server?
fields.explanation: FTP stands for File Transfer Protocol, and can directly upload files to a web server.

fields.text: What does a hard disk defragmenter do?
fields.explanation: Data on the disk that has been split up is moved together, meaning there is less movement needed by the hard disk head to read the data.

fields.text: What is the Windows page file otherwise known as?
fields.explanation: Virtual memory is space on the hard disk that is used when the physical memory (RAM) is all in use.

fields.text: Which part of a laser printer heats and melts toner to the paper?
fields.explanation: The fuser unit gets hot in order to fuse the powdered toner (that is earlier transfered to the paper) to the page so it does not smear.

fields.text: Which of the following can be used to administer user accounts on a Microsoft Server 2003 network?
fields.explanation: Active directory can be used for a large number of tasks, including administering computer and user accounts on a domain (or multiple domains).

fields.text: What was the original purpose of a screen-saver?
fields.explanation: On older monitors static images would be burned into the screen causing permanent damage. Screensavers were designed to keep a moving image on the screen that would not burn in.

fields.text: A laptop generally has which type of screen?
fields.explanation: Laptops usually have LCD screens. LCD stands for Liquid Crystal Display.

fields.text: If a DVD ROM drive equipped computer will not play DVD's, what might you try?
fields.explanation: Codecs allow DVD's to play on a computer - they are not always installed with the operating system for legal reasons, and must then be installed afterwards.

fields.text: Which of these is an older connection used for printers?
fields.explanation: Parallel cables have wide connectors and were used to connect printers and scanners. It is more common to use a USB connection now.

fields.text: What might you use to connect and view the desktop of another Windows computer?
fields.explanation: RDP stands for Remote Desktop Protocol, which allows remote connections to networked PC's and devices.
RDP stands for Remote Desktop Protocol, which allows remote connections to networked PC's and devices.
Hyper Text Transfer Protocol is a data communication protocol used by the internet.
Hyper Text Markup Language is a programming language used to code webpages, and is understood by web browsers such as Internet Explorer.
usb (Universal Serial Bus) can be used to connect all types of hardware to a PC. The techbology is contantly being updated becoming faster with each release.

fields.text: What program would usually be used in Windows to open a file with the extension: .txt
fields.explanation: Notepad is a basic text editor in Windows, and creates text only files (no colours, fonts etc) with the txt extension.
Internet Protocol is a protocol used by the internet for sending data packets.

fields.text: Which of these cannot be changed in a computer's settings?
fields.explanation: The MAC address is built into the network card so unless that is changes, the MAC address will remain the same.

fields.text: How many kilobytes are in a megabyte?
fields.explanation: There are exactly 1024 kilobytes in a megabyte.

fields.text: What is the size of a single sided, single layered DVD?
fields.explanation: The standard size of a DVD disc is 4.7gb.

fields.text: What does POP stand for in POP3?
fields.explanation: Post Office Protocol is used by a computer/device to download e-mails from a remote server.
SMTP is used to send e-mails across the internet.
OpenGL (Open Graphics Library) is a cross platform API for creating graphics.

fields.text: How might related data be efficiently stored on a hard disk drive for faster access?
fields.explanation: Parts of a single file that are spread out over the hard disk can be arranged so they are stored in order. Subsequent access is a lot faster.

fields.text: What is the MBR on a PC hard disk?
fields.explanation: The Master Boot Record is used for storing partition information and/or startup information for the operating system.

fields.text: How might an unrecoverable BIOS password be reset?
fields.explanation: Removing the battery for a short while will normally reset the BIOS password. You can also reset the BIOS password using jumpers on the motherboard.

fields.text: If a laptop with an encrypted hard disk (but no available password) was found, how could this be circumvented to be used again?
fields.explanation: The only way to use an encrypted hard disk without the password, is to erase the contents. Data cannot be recovered.

fields.text: Which of the following is NOT a programming language?
fields.explanation: WYSIWYG stands for 'What You See Is What You Get' - often webpages are build using WYSIWYG - it simply means when developing, you see the product as it will be seen by the user, rather than looking at programming code.

fields.text: In a laser printer, the paper is not being fed in from the paper tray. What would you most likely need to replace?
fields.explanation: Although potentially any of the above could prevent paper being fed if faulty, the most common is the pickup rollers, which wear down after a lot of use and become to smooth to pickup the paper.
The boot sector is normally used to start the Operating System (OS). Information from it is moved into RAM to be used.

fields.text: Which of the following is usually the fastest?
fields.explanation: The CPU (Central Processing Unit, or Processor) is normally the fastest part of a computer and does most (or all) or the calculations the computer must compute.

fields.text: What might you do to ensure a network printer is accessible to users at all times?
fields.explanation: Assigning a static IP address using DHCP will mean every time the printer is switched on, it can be found using the same IP address.

fields.text: How is data stored on a standard hard disk drive?
fields.explanation: Magnetic charge is used to set each bit on or off (1 or 0). This is the data stored in its most basic form, and 'on or off' is the only form of data a computer can actually understand, as it is, in essence, and electronic device.

fields.text: A user cannot run installation programs on their networked computer. How could the administrator change this?
fields.explanation: Users can have different access permissions set up for many different files and settings, at varying levels of control.

A computer can not (at it's basic level) work with numbers or characters etc, only ON or OFF values (represented by 1's and 0's in binary language). Binary is a low level programming language as it is close to what the computer can understand.

fields.text: What is an OU used for in Active Directory?
fields.explanation: For example, OU's for a business domain might include 'Sales Team', 'Clerical Staff' etc and each OU's objects could be given access to different files on the network.

fields.text: How is a computer account added to a domain?
fields.explanation: The computer must be manually added onto the domain, using the operating system's build in tool.
The dead pixel may be off (black) or may be the wrong colour. This is quite common on LCD screens.
It can be used to fix problems with Windows that cannot be sorted when the operating system is in use (such ask disk checking and repair).

fields.text: What is the usual way to access Recovery Console?
fields.explanation: Booting from the Windows CD will allow access to the recovery console.

fields.text: Why was the QWERTY keyboard designed with its layout as it is?
fields.explanation: The layout of keys was designed to stop the long key arms of letter pairs (ch, sh etc) becoming stuck togther when pressed in quick succession, in order that faster typists had fewer problems. It is NOT, contrary to popular belief, to slow down the typist.

fields.text: Which would help boost a wireless network signal?
fields.explanation: A wireless repeater will 'refresh' the wireless signal by sending it out again, boosting the area covered.

fields.text: Which of the following would BEST help secure a home wireless network from malicious 'piggybacking'?
fields.explanation: As long as the network is secure with a password, it is unlikely there will be any intrusions (although this is not guaranteed).

A large network can be split into VLANs (for example by departments in an organisation). Each VLAN is treated as a network itself. This helps minimise data flowing round the main network infrastructure.

fields.text: What might you use RDP for?
fields.explanation: RDP (Remote Desktop Protocol) allows connection to remote computers and devices on the network.

fields.text: What is a shell script written for?
fields.explanation: Scripts are processed by the command line interpreter.

fields.text: Which of the following is NOT true of a proxy?
fields.explanation: A proxy does NOT allow more data to pass through more quickly - it is used to restrict data received/transmitted from a computer/device.
Firewire (IEEE1394) is a technology often used for transferring data to/from multimedia devices such as digital camcorders.
MSConfig is a good tool for diagnosing Windows startup problems as it allows the turning off of certain features.

fields.text: What is event viewer used for?
fields.explanation: Event view is a detailed logging system for Windows operating systems. It contains information for many actions performed by the operating system itself and software installed on it. It provides information of any error messages along with the times they happened.

fields.text: What might you try FIRST if windows reports corrupt files?
fields.explanation: Running the chkdsk /r (check disk) command from the recovery console will normally repair any corrupt file problems in the operating system.
FTP (File Transfer Protocol) allows direct transfer of files to a remote server (often used for quickly uploading webpages to a web server).

fields.text: In order to use an extended desktop over two monitors, what is needed on a PC?
fields.explanation: The dual screen card will allow two monitors to be connected and the display spanned over two monitors.

fields.text: If you wish to clone your computer's display onto a projector, what could you use (on most computers/monitors/projectors)?
fields.explanation: A VGA splitter will split the signal from the graphics adapter on the computer so it can be clones onto the projector.

fields.text: What is multitasking in an operating system?
fields.explanation: A computer will allow multiple tasks to be running at the same time. This is called multitasking.
If a webpage is cached, it does not need to be fully downloaded from the server the next time it is viewed, as some or all of the page will be in cached.

fields.text: What process can be restarted if Windows has crashed, in order that the start menu and icons reappear?
fields.explanation: If explorer.exe crashes or is stopped, the start menu and icons will not be visible. Starting the process back up will resolve this.

fields.text: How would you allow specific data to pass through Windows Firewall?
fields.explanation: Exceptions provide just that - an exception to the rule. Everything is blocked by a firewall unless the firewall knows to let it through using an exception.

For example, an operating system may make and index of all files on the hard disk. When a search is performed for a filename, the operating system simply searches the index rather than searching the entire hard disk for the file name.
The name by which the wireless name can be addess onto a networked device is called the SSID (Service Set Identification).

fields.text: Why might you roll back a driver?
fields.explanation: Problematic drivers can be rolled back in modern versions of Windows. If a driver causes problems with the operating system or hardware, it can be rolled back to a previous version.

fields.text: What is a system restore point used for in Windows?
fields.explanation: If Windows suddenly will not boot, as long as restore points are turned on, the system can be restored to a working state.
FAT stands for File Allocation Table. The 32 means 32 bit.

fields.text: When would safemode be LEAST useful?
fields.explanation: Safemode allows certain features to be used without booting into Windows. It is used for repairing/diagnosing problems with Windows and comes on the Windows disk as a bootable tool.

fields.text: From where could you map a network drive in Windows?
fields.explanation: Right clicking 'My Computer' or using the menu within 'My Computer' allows mapping of a network drive. This can also be done at command prompt using the 'net use' command.

fields.text: Why might you map a network drive?
fields.explanation: Mapping drives allows any shared folder to be used like a separate drive. The shared folder is usually on a remote computer or server.

fields.text: What does the registry key HKCR contain?
fields.explanation: Allows certain file types to be associated with applications (ie Word documents are associate with Microsoft Office Word).
The file can be used to automate the running of command line commands eg for copying files, mapping drives etc.
Collision on a data network are very common and reducing them is one of the many goals of the network manager.

fields.text: Which is NOT a difference between XP and 98
fields.explanation: The file extension '.exe' has remained consistant across all versions of Windows.

fields.text: What was the first Microsoft Operating System?
fields.explanation: DOS, or 'Disk Operating System'

fields.text: Which operating system is NOT based on DOS?
fields.explanation: Windows XP is not based on DOS. Windows Me 'pretended' not to be based on DOS, but it was.

fields.text: Which of the following companies have NEVER produced personal computers?
fields.explanation: They build hardware and firmware, but never full personal computers. All the other companies have produced PC's.

fields.text: Which of the following is NOT an operating system?
fields.explanation: VMWare is used for desktop virtualisation.

fields.text: What might be applied to software to fix a specific issue?
fields.explanation: A patch will repair problems with software. After a piece of software is released, there are often problems which are not found during testing. Patches are then released by the developer to fix these problems.

fields.text: Which best describes a Trojan horse?
fields.explanation: The name is based on the military move by the Greeks in the Trojan war using a large wooden horse (Or rabbit if you have seen Monty Python and the Holy Grail!) to hide soldiers.

fields.text: Which of the following statements is TRUE about a worm and a virus?
fields.explanation: A worm can e-mail itself using contacts stored on a computer, without the user even doing anything.
DOS was Microsoft's first operating system, and was used as a basis for a number of it's future operating systems.
An Active X control is run within a web browser, and is used for certain features on some websites or applications.
A Java applet is run from a web browser and is not a standalone application. It might be a clock display on a web page for example.

fields.text: What can Tweak UI be used for?
fields.explanation: Tweak UI is a free tool provided by Microsoft which provides Windows users more control over visual aspects of their operating system.

fields.text: What device in a PC stores a MAC address?
fields.explanation: The Network Interface Card (NIC) holds the MAC address (A.K.A. the Hardware Address).

fields.text: How can a MAC address be changed in a PC?
fields.explanation: Changing the network interface is one way to change the MAC/hardware address on a computer. It can also be done using software.

fields.text: What does mounting a disk drive achieve?
fields.explanation: Mounting a drive allows the file system access to it.
A partition will appear to the user as a separate disk drive. It may use a different file system and/or contain a separate operating system.
Technically speaking, a server serves clients. These may be computers, mobile devices, printers, users etc.

fields.text: What special piece of software allows hardware to communicate with software?
fields.explanation: A driver is normally provided by the manufacturer of the software and allows specified operating systems to interact with the hardware. Modern operating systems do come with a limited set of basic drivers so some devices will work without installing the drivers from the manufacturer.
The PCI ports on a PC can be used to connect all kinds of devices including network cards, TV cards, wireless network cards etc.
PCIe - Peripheral Component Interconnect - is a faster more modern version of the standard PCI connection.

fields.text: What might you use PCMCIA for?
fields.explanation: PCMCIA, or PC Card, is usually used for network adapters, but has other uses.
Some users have the need to boot from multiple operating systems (eg Windows 7 and Ubuntu 11).

fields.text: What is a disk sector on a hard disk?
fields.explanation: A disk sector is a physical storage area on a hard disk drive.

fields.text: How is data stored on a hard disk drive?
fields.explanation: Data is stored magnetically on the disk platters, and by the read/write head.
BSOD stands for Blue Screen of Death, and results in a computer being restarted after a hardware or software error that the operating system cannot recover from.

fields.text: Which is most likely to cause a Blue Screen of Death?
fields.explanation: Faulty hardware is a common cause of the BSOD, along with faulty drivers.

fields.text: Which of the following is most likely to require its own fan?
fields.explanation: The processor will always have its own cooling system as it becomes very hot during computer use.

fields.text: What key should be pressed to access safe mode at startup in Windows?
fields.explanation: F8 is the shortcut key that allows various boot options such as safe mode, safe mode with networking, and command prompt.

fields.text: Which company produces processors for personal computers?
fields.explanation: Intel produce processors such as the Celeron, Core 3,5,7 and Pentium.
SQL (Structured Query Language) is used for querying databases to fetch results.
ASCII - American Standard Code for Information Interchange
10 means 10Mbps bandwidth. The T stands for Twisted-pair, as ethernet networking uses twisted pairs of cables.
DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) is used to automatically assign IP addresses to devices on the network.
An ISO is created from an optical disk, and can be used to recreate exact copies of the original disc.
Token ring is a network protocol whereby data is transmitted when the token is held. The token is passed around in a ring between devices/nodes.

fields.text: What is NOT true of a hubs compared to switches?
fields.explanation: The above statement is NOT true as a switch can never act as a server.
Ubuntu is commonly used as an introduction to Linux for first time users, as it is simple to use and very user friendly.
Fedora is a very popular Linux based operating system along with software accompanying it.

fields.text: What is the job of a network repeater?
fields.explanation: A network transmission will deteriorate over distance and so a repeated amplifies the signal before sending it on.

fields.text: What is a routing table used for?
fields.explanation: The routing table builds up a list of hosts and the route that is needed to reach the hosts.

fields.text: Which of the following has a degaussing feature?
fields.explanation: A CRT monitor is affected by magnetic fields - degaussing is used to correct any problems caused my magnetic interference.
The word 'bit' is short for 'binary digit'. A bit is a single value of on/off (or 1/0).

fields.text: When referring to window layout, what does the D stand for in MDI?
fields.explanation: An MDI is a Multiple Document Interface. For example in word processing software, if all document windows were opened within a parent windows, that would be an MDI.

fields.text: What do the D and S stand for in DIMM and SIMM?
fields.explanation: Dual Inline Memory Module, Single Inline Memory Module.

fields.text: What is Windows 8's server counterpart operating system named?
fields.explanation: It was codenamed Windows Server 8, but its release name is Windows Server 2012, in keeping with the naming convention used since Windows Server 2003. Before that was Windows 2000 Server.

fields.text: What is the Windows 8 user interface based on?
fields.explanation: The Windows 8 user interface will be based on Microsoft's Metro design language, and will be based more on typography than imagery.

fields.text: What is the purpose of a subnet mask?
fields.explanation: A subnet mast looks something like this: 255.255.255.0

fields.text: Which of the following subnet masks belongs to a class C network?
Which of the following is a popular anti malware program?
fields.explanation: There is a free version of MalwareBytes. It is a very popular tool for malware removal.

fields.text: What does ReadyBoost do in Windows Vista (and later)?
fields.explanation: ReadyBoost allows a formatted USB drive to be used as RAM.

fields.text: Which accessory, included in Windows 7, allows taking of a snapshot from a selected area of the screen?
fields.explanation: The snipping tool is vey useful and is much less cumbersome that taking a full print screen.

fields.text: Which accessory, included in Windows 7, displays a post-it style note onscreen that can be edited?
fields.explanation: Sticky Notes can be edited, and are a useful alternative to real post it notes.

fields.text: Which company is named after a US city?
fields.explanation: The word Cisco is short for San Francisco.

fields.text: What was the first product Apple sold?
fields.explanation: The Apple Computer is now referred to as the Apple I. It was not sold with keyboard, casing etc.

fields.text: When did Apple's first computer go on sale?
fields.explanation: It was simply calle the Apple Computer. It is now referred to as the Apple I.

fields.text: What is the original name of Apple Inc.?
fields.explanation: Apple Computer was founded in 1976.

fields.text: Which command can you use in Windows 7 to list running processes?
fields.explanation: Tasklist.exe will list all running processes. Use 'tasklist /s <hostname>' to show the same information for a remote computer.

fields.text: Which command can you use in Windows 7 to kill running processes?
fields.explanation: Taskkill.exe will end a specified running processes. Use 'tasklist' to simply view the processes before using taskkill to kill them.

fields.text: What does the command 'Netstat -a' do in Windows?
fields.explanation: 'Netstat -a' shows all the connections to your computer including yourself. You can use it to see if anyone else is connected to your computer too.

fields.text: In Windows 8, what is the name of the tiled area that shows your apps?
fields.explanation: It is possible to move from 'Start' to the desktop by moving the mouse into the bottom left of the screen.

fields.text: Which Microsoft application uses PST files?
fields.explanation: Microsoft Outlook stores a lot of information in a PST file, such as contacts, e-mails etc. It is known to cause problems in exchange server environments as the PST can be saved off the network, and therefore insecurely.

fields.text: How many printable characters are included in ASCII?
fields.explanation: There are 95 printable characters in ASCII (Many are not printable, for example one character represents a 'beep' sound).
NSlookup can be used for example to find a hostname for a given IP address.

fields.text: What is disk striping related to?
fields.explanation: Disk Striping separates data into several blocks spread over multiple partitions on multiple disk drives.

fields.text: Which is NOT a layer of the ISO/OSI network model?
fields.explanation: The layers are: physical, data link, network, transport, session, presentation, application.

fields.text: Which of the following is NOT a layer of the ISO/OSI network model?
fields.explanation: The layers are: physical, data link, network, transport, session, presentation, application.
Colossus was used in the war to crack codes.

fields.text: What would be used to connect a computer to a data point?
fields.explanation: A straight through cable is used to connect a computer to a standard data point (which in turn would be patched to a switch).
For example, a gateway is used to connect to the internet.

fields.text: How many individual wires are in a cat5e cable?
fields.explanation: 8 wires in total - white+orange, orange, white+green, blue, white+blue, green, white+brown, brown.

fields.text: Why are wires in network cables twisted?
fields.explanation: Twisted cables will act as a form of interference reduction from external sources.
A virtual disk is not a physical storage device, and has no physical presence (although of course a physical disk is needed to contain the virtual disk and its contents).
It allows a Windows users and administrators much more control than the built in command line tools in Windows.
It stands for GNU's Not Unix
Gnome and KDE are desktop environments used in various versions of Linux.
Colossus was used to crack military codes used in World War 2.

An API provides an interface for developers to interract with another application, website, system etc. Eg an API for ebay would allow ebay applications developed by third parties, to integrate corectly with ebay.
An example of non-volatile storage is a hard disk drive. Volatile storage, on the other hand (for example RAM), loses data when power is removed.

fields.text: What type of Ethernet cable would you use to connect two devices of the same type?
fields.explanation: For example to connect a switch to a switch or a computer to a computer, a crossover cable is needed.

fields.text: What is iEEE 1394 better known as?
fields.explanation: Firewire is a technology used for multimedia data transfer. It is simillar in many ways to USB.

fields.text: Add the following in hexadecimal: Ah + Dh
fields.explanation: Hexadecimal is base 16, so numbers go from 0-F (F being equivalent to 15 in decimal).

fields.text: What is a tree when discussing domains?
fields.explanation: A tree is a collection of domains. The parent of a tree is a forest (which contains multiple domain trees).

fields.text: What might the term 'non-buffered' relate to?
fields.explanation: Non-buffered is a feature of RAM (Random Access Memory) or physical memory.
Computers can work together on certains tasks. They work in a cluster.
It is a name service for NetBIOS.
Javascript runs on the computer, rather than on the server, and so is 'client side'.

fields.text: How might you register a DLL file in Windows?
fields.explanation: Registering a DLL file makes it available to the operating system.
A DLL file contains shared resources that can be used by various programs on a computer.

fields.text: Which of the following applies to a DLL file?
fields.explanation: The DLL file contains shared resources.
SQL (Structured Query Language) is used for querying databases to fetch results.

fields.text: What is a hard disk platter?
fields.explanation: The platter is a physical disc on which data is written. There are usually several platters in a hard disk drive.
The jumper allows certain settings to be changed using a small device that joins pins together.

fields.text: What does a hard drive spindle do?
fields.explanation: Each platter (disc) inside a hard disk drive is turned by the spindle.

fields.text: In a laser printer, what does the imaging drum do?
fields.explanation: The imaging drum is charged in areas so in effect what is printed is first attracted onto the imaging drum. It is then transferred to the paper.

fields.text: In laser printers, what does the laser do?
fields.explanation: The laser precisely charges areas of the drum, which then attracts the toner to create the image, ready to be transferred to paper.
The difference engine was a mechanical calculator/computer.
The difference engine (which was a large mechanical computer/calculator) was invented by Charles Babbage.
AMD are best known for their processors, which include the Athlon, Duron and Sempron.
Intel was founded by Gordon Moore and Robert Noyce in California in 1968.

fields.text: What is a daemon on a UNIX system?
fields.explanation: A daemon does not require a user interface.

fields.text: In DOS what does deltree do?
fields.explanation: Deltree (delete tree) is a Microsoft Dos command used for deleting entire directories (folders) and subdirectories.

fields.text: What is Microsoft's first 32bit operating system?
fields.explanation: Windows NT 3.1 was released in 1993.
PC-DOS was Microsoft's big break - a licensing oversight meant IBM did not have exclusive use of PC-DOS, and it could be sold to other competitors by Microsoft.

fields.text: Who originally created the software that became MS-DOS?
fields.explanation: The original name of Microsoft DOS was QDOS (Quick and Dirty Operating System). It was bought by Microsoft and then sold to IBM for use with their hardware.
The IANA allocates internet IP addresses
IIS is a set of internet services for use with servers running Microsoft Windows Server.
Direct X is used to create 2D and 3D graphics and sound for use in applications.

fields.text: What is System Locked Preinstallation used for?
fields.explanation: When receiving a new computer, you will often receive a restore disc. This can usually only be used in the original computer because of system Locked Preinstallation.

fields.text: What might sysprep be used for?
fields.explanation: Once a computer is sysprepped, an image can be take from it that can then be used as a base for setting up other computers.

fields.text: What is RIS in Windows XP?
fields.explanation: RIS allows installation of a Microsoft operating system remotely.
